### Inefficient HTTP Server Request Handling (Anti-Pattern)

Source: https://github.com/pauljphilp/effectpatterns/blob/main/content/published/build-a-basic-http-server.mdx

This example illustrates an anti-pattern where a new Effect runtime is created for each incoming HTTP request. This is highly inefficient and negates the benefits of Effect-TS's Layer system for managing dependencies and resources. The `GreeterLive` layer is provided within the request handler, leading to repeated setup costs.

```typescript
import * as http from "http";
import { Effect, Layer } from "effect";
import { GreeterLive } from "./somewhere";

// ❌ WRONG: This rebuilds the GreeterLive layer on every request.
const server = http.createServer((_req, res) => {
  const requestEffect = Effect.succeed("Hello!").pipe(
    Effect.provide(GreeterLive), // Providing the layer here is inefficient
  );
  Effect.runPromise(requestEffect).then((msg) => res.end(msg));
});
```

