To double-check we’re on the same page, here’s how the current backend is structured and why it differs a bit from the bare‑bones snippets in the docs:

---

### 1. Router + Server Layer

We now export an `httpApp` from `apps/server/src/http/app.ts` so the server can consume the fully composed router:

```ts
export const httpApp = HttpRouter.toHttpApp(
  router.pipe(
    HttpRouter.use(HttpMiddleware.searchParamsParser),
    HttpRouter.use(jsonErrorMiddleware),
    HttpRouter.use(rateLimitMiddleware()),
    HttpRouter.use(requestLoggingMiddleware),
  ),
);
```

Then `apps/server/src/http/server.ts` serves that app using `HttpServer.serveEffect` and a Node server layer—following the exact pattern in the Effect docs, including the address logger:

```ts
export const Live = Layer.scopedDiscard(
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const { port } = yield* Config;
    const nodeServerLayer = NodeHttpServer.layer(() => http.createServer(), {
      port,
    });

    yield* httpApp.pipe(
      Effect.flatMap((app) =>
        HttpServer.serveEffect(app).pipe(
          Effect.zipRight(
            HttpServer.addressFormattedWith((address) =>
              Effect.logInfo(`http server listening on ${address}`),
            ),
          ),
          Effect.annotateLogs({ component: 'http', port }),
        ),
      ),
      Effect.provideLayer(nodeServerLayer),
    );
  }),
);
```

---

### 2. `main.ts` vs. Example Snippets

The doc snippets you pasted are great for a “router + server, nothing else” setup. Our reality is heavier—we have to:

- Provide dozens of live layers (DB pool, stores, GitHub clients, rate limiter, SSE hub, etc.).
- Run migrations before we start the HTTP listener.
- Kick off background schedulers and reconciler loops (and keep them scoped so they clean up when the process exits).

That’s why `main.ts` does the extra work:

```ts
const servicesLayer = Layer.mergeAll(
  ConfigLive,
  LoggerLive,
  DbLive,
  MigrationsLive,
  HttpRateLimiterLive,
  EventsHubLive,
  WebhookDeliveriesLive,
  ReposStoreLive,
  RunsStoreLive,
  JobsStoreLive,
  GithubClientLive,
  GithubWebhookVerifierLive,
  GithubRunHydratorLive,
  RunHydrationQueueLive,
  RateLimiterLive,
  RunsBackfillLive,
  BackfillSchedulerLive,
  ReconcilerLive,
  WorkflowRunHandlerLive,
  WorkflowJobHandlerLive,
);

const serverLayer = Layer.mergeAll(servicesLayer, HttpServerLive);

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  yield* runMigrations;
  yield* runBackfillScheduler.pipe(Effect.forkScoped);
  yield* startReconciler.pipe(Effect.forkScoped);
  const config = yield* Config;
  yield* Effect.logInfo(`server boot on port ${config.port}`);
  yield* Effect.never;
}).pipe(withRequestId('bootstrap'), Effect.scoped, Effect.provide(serverLayer));

runMain(program);
```

This may look unfamiliar compared to the tiny snippet, but it’s still applying the same building blocks:

- We supply the same router→server layer via `HttpServerLive` (which already follows the snippet pattern).
- We use `Effect.scoped` so every `Layer.scoped` we merged (including `HttpServerLive`) stays alive until shutdown.
- The `Effect.never` at the end is the standard way to keep a scoped runtime running forever (comparable to `Layer.launch` in the docs).

If we wanted to mirror the docs even more literally, the only change would be to pull the server launch out of the `Effect.gen` body:

```ts
const program = Effect.scoped(
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    yield* runMigrations;
    yield* Layer.launch(serverLayer);
    yield* runBackfillScheduler.pipe(Effect.forkScoped);
    yield* startReconciler.pipe(Effect.forkScoped);
    yield* Effect.never;
  }),
).pipe(withRequestId('bootstrap'));

runMain(program);
```

Both forms keep the server alive for the life of the scope; the choice is mostly stylistic. If you’d prefer this `Layer.launch` shape, say the word and I can swap it in—otherwise the current version is already correct for the Effect platform patterns while handling our extra moving parts.

