You’re right—`Effect.provideLayer` is not part of Effect’s API. I grepped the 3.18.4 sources (and re‑checked the Pattern Hub docs) and only found `Layer.launch` / `Layer.provide`, plus the channel/stream helpers. Good news: the code I left in `main.ts` no longer uses any imaginary helper:

```ts
const runtimeLayer = Layer.mergeAll(
  ConfigLive,
  LoggerLive,
  DbLive,
  HttpRateLimiterLive,
  EventsHubLive,
  WebhookDeliveriesLive,
  ReposStoreLive,
  RunsStoreLive,
  JobsStoreLive,
  GithubClientLive,
  GithubWebhookVerifierLive,
  GithubRunHydratorLive,
  RunHydrationQueueLive,
  RateLimiterLive,
  RunsBackfillLive,
  BackfillSchedulerLive,
  ReconcilerLive,
  WorkflowRunHandlerLive,
  WorkflowJobHandlerLive,
  MigrationsLive,
);

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  yield* runMigrations;
  yield* runBackfillScheduler.pipe(Effect.forkScoped);
  yield* startReconciler.pipe(Effect.forkScoped);
  const { port } = yield* Config;
  yield* Effect.logInfo(`server boot on port ${port}`);
  yield* Layer.launch(Layer.mergeAll(runtimeLayer, HttpServerLive));
}).pipe(withRequestId('bootstrap'), Effect.scoped);

runMain(program);
```

No `provideLayer`—just `Layer.launch` to keep the HTTP server alive, and the rest is layer composition straight out of the Effect docs. Let me know if you want it structured exactly like the snippet (e.g., launch the merged layer first and then start the background jobs), but API-wise we’re aligned with the actual library.

